so   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Rees  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Rice  .","German: habitational name from a place in the Rhineland called Rees.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Andreas  ."]}]},{"name":"\"Gôch\"","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Pawel, Zuzanna, Zygmunt.","North German: habitational name from any of various minor places which get their names from an ancient Germanic element <i>goch</i>, <i>gog</i> ‘marsh, bog, fen’.","Polish: from a pet form of various personal names beginning with <i>Go-</i>, such as <i>Gościsław</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Gotch","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>coch</i>, <i>goch</i> ‘red(-haired)’; see   Gooch   3.","English (Northamptonshire): variant of   Gooch   1 and 2.","Americanized form of German <b>Götsch</b> (see   Gotsch  )."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the